Preheat your oven to 220°C/200°C fan/gas mark 7.

Chop the @grilling cheese{200%g} into 2cm chunks.

Pop them into a #bowl{} of @water{} to soak.

Chop the @broccoli{1}(cut into florets) into florets (little trees).

Boil a large #pot{} of salted water for the rice.

Add the @rice{150%g} and cook for ~{10-12%minutes}.

Drain in a #sieve{} and pop back in the pot. Cover with a #lid{} and leave to the side until ready to serve.

> TIP: If you're in a hurry you can boil the water in your kettle.

Pop the broccoli florets onto a lined #baking tray{}. Drizzle with @oil{to taste}, season with @pepper{to taste} then toss to coat.

Spread out in one layer and roast on the top shelf of your oven until edges are slightly charred, ~{10-15%minutes}.

Meanwhile, halve, peel and chop the @onion{1}(peeled and chopped) into small pieces.

Peel and grate the @garlic{2}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{}).

Trim the @scallion{1} and thinly slice.

Heat a drizzle of @oil{to taste} in a pan on medium-high heat.

Pat down the cheese with some #kitchen paper{}.

Once the oil is hot, add the cheese to the pan.

Fry until golden all over, ~{4-6%minutes}. Turn every 1-2 mins.

Once the cheese is golden, remove to a bowl, pop your pan back on medium-high heat and add a drizzle of @oil{to taste}.

Add the onion to the pan and cook until softened, ~{4-5%minutes}.

Stir in the garlic, @korma curry paste{1%sachet} and @tomato paste{1%pack} and cook for ~{1%minute}.

Add 100ml @water{100%ml} with @sugar{1%tsp} (double both for 4p) then stir in the @vegetable stock{1%sachet}.

Bring to the boil and simmer until reduced by a third, ~{4-5%minutes}.

Stir in half the @creme fraiche{62.5%g} (double for 4p), the broccoli and the cheese and cook until piping hot, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Taste the curry and add more @salt{to taste}, @pepper{to taste} or @sugar{to taste} if you feel it needs it.

Add a splash of @water{to taste} if it's thickened too much.

Fluff up the rice with a #fork{}, then spoon into #bowls{}.

Top with the curry and a sprinkling of scallions.